{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586897"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:39:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:39:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15100"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15100"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.04,0.09,0.04,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85610"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7788"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69903"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1894"},{"type":"tags","id":"2066"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5366"},{"type":"tags","id":"8131"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19001"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19003"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85610"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProstate specific antigen (PSA) exists in the blood in multiple forms. The free PSA percentage is calculated as: (free PSA \u00f7 total PSA) \u00d7 100.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following free PSA percentages is associated with the lowest risk of prostate cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["\u003E50%","25-49%","15-24%","10-14%","5-9%"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe free PSA percentage helps differentiate between benign prostatic hyperplasia and prostate cancer. A \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003E50%\u003C/strong\u003E free PSA percentage indicates the lowest risk of prostate cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003E25-49%\u003C/strong\u003E is generally reassuring, while \u003Cstrong\u003E15-24%\u003C/strong\u003E represents an intermediate risk. \u003Cstrong\u003E10-14%\u003C/strong\u003E suggests an increased risk of malignancy, and \u003Cstrong\u003E5-9%\u003C/strong\u003E indicates the highest risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn benign conditions, more PSA exists in the unbound (free) form. Conversely, in prostate cancer, there is typically a lower percentage of free PSA. Therefore, a higher free PSA percentage is more suggestive of benign disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A free PSA to total PSA ratio \u003E25% indicates a lower risk of prostate cancer","Free PSA percentage helps distinguish between benign prostatic hyperplasia and prostate cancer","Lower free PSA percentages suggest higher risk of malignancy"],"references":["Yim K, Ma C, Carlsson S, Lilja H, Mucci L, Penney K, Kibel AS, Eggener S, Preston MA. Free PSA and Clinically Significant and Fatal Prostate Cancer in the PLCO Screening Trial. J Urol. 2023 Oct;210(4):630-638. doi: 10.1097/JU.0000000000003603. Epub 2023 Jun 29. PMID: 37384841; PMCID: PMC10894656.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relations